explanation: OS_CHECK_POINTER — likely a macro. Must inspect its definition to ensure it does not assign to the parameter identifier sock_prop (a macro could expand to code that modifies the parameter variable). OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET — likely a macro that indexes into OS_global_stream_table using token; its expansion could modify token or other temporaries or even the passed-in pointer variable, so its body must be checked. OS_SocketGetInfo_Impl — although shown as a callee, it could be an inline or macro implementation; if inlined it might contain code that assigns to sock_prop (the parameter variable) via expansion. OS_ObjectIdGetById — may be implemented as a macro or wrapper; check its signature/definition to ensure it does not perform assignments to the target function parameters (sock_id or sock_prop) via side-effecting macro expansion. OS_ObjectIdRelease — similar rationale: if implemented as a macro it could alter local/state in a way that affects parameters. OS_socket_prop_t — the pointee type definition is needed to confirm sock_prop is a pointer type and to verify whether any operations could be interpreted as writing to the pointer itself (e.g., unusual typedefs or overloaded macros). osal_id_t — need the typedef to confirm sock_id is passed by value (so cannot modify caller) and to ensure it is not a macro that could cause unexpected assignment. OS_object_token_t — token type definition (in case macros or inline functions reference token and the expansion affects passed arguments). OS_common_record_t — definition required to check whether use of record->name_entry or other fields involves macros that might alias or reassign the sock_prop parameter. OS_global_stream_table — the macro OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET may reference this symbol; its definition/context is required to see macro expansions. memset — confirm it is the standard function (not a macro) and that its usage (memset(sock_prop,...)) only writes through the pointer, not reassigning the pointer variable. strncpy — confirm it is the standard function (not a macro) and that it writes to *sock_prop (the object) but does not modify the pointer variable. These symbols collectively allow determining whether any invoked macros/inline expansions or type definitions perform assignment to the formal parameters (sock_id or sock_prop) themselves, which is the MISRA concern (pointer object may be modified, but the pointer parameter variable shall not be assigned to).
